Security engineers juggle a lot: logs, alerts, audits, tools, frameworks, compliance documents. AI assistants like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini can streamline workflows — but only if you prompt them well.
Without well-crafted prompts, AI responses tend toward excessive jargon or generic compliance language that isn&rsquo;t actually useful.
Here&rsquo;s a cheat sheet of prompting patterns that work.
1. When You Want an Explanation Use case: Quickly understand a new tool, concept, or attack vector.
Template:
&ldquo;Explain [concept/tool/attack] like I&rsquo;m presenting it to [audience]. Add analogies and examples.&rdquo;
Examples:
&ldquo;Explain Zero Trust Architecture like I&rsquo;m writing for a developer who has never worked in security. Use real-world analogies, not marketing language.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Explain the difference between authentication and authorization like I&rsquo;m talking to a non-technical startup founder.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Explain SQL injection like I&rsquo;m doing a 5-minute lunch-and-learn for backend engineers.&rdquo;
Why it works: Specifying the audience forces the model to calibrate depth and vocabulary. Adding &ldquo;analogies and examples&rdquo; prevents abstract answers.
2. When You Want a Comparison Template:
&ldquo;Compare [A] vs [B] for [specific use case]. Give me a pros/cons table and a recommendation for [my context].&rdquo;
Examples:
&ldquo;Compare SAST vs DAST for a startup with a small security team. Pros/cons table + which to prioritize first.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Compare WAF vs API gateway for protecting a public-facing REST API. Include cost considerations.&rdquo;
3. When You Want a Threat Model Template:
&ldquo;Act as a security architect. Threat model this system: [brief description]. List the top 5 attack vectors using STRIDE. For each, suggest a control.&rdquo;
Example:
&ldquo;Act as a security architect. Threat model a SaaS app where users upload CSV files that get processed by a Python backend and stored in S3. Top 5 STRIDE threats + controls.&rdquo;
4. When You&rsquo;re Writing a Security Report Template:
&ldquo;Rewrite this finding for a [technical/non-technical] audience. Keep the severity rating. Make the impact concrete and avoid jargon: [paste finding]&rdquo;
Example:
&ldquo;Rewrite this finding for a non-technical CISO. Keep the CVSS score. Make the business impact clear in two sentences: [paste your raw finding]&rdquo;
5. When You&rsquo;re Reviewing Code for Security Issues Template:
&ldquo;Review this code for security vulnerabilities. List each issue with: vulnerability type, line reference, exploitability (high/med/low), and a one-line fix. [paste code]&rdquo;
Don&rsquo;t just say &ldquo;find bugs.&rdquo; Tell it what format to respond in — otherwise you get a wall of prose.
6. When You&rsquo;re Doing Incident Response Template:
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m investigating a potential [attack type] incident. Here are the indicators: [paste IOCs/logs]. Help me build a timeline, identify scope, and list next steps.&rdquo;
7. When You Need Policy or Documentation Template:
&ldquo;Write a [document type] for a [company size/type] company. Use plain language. Include sections for: [list sections]. Tone: direct, not corporate-speak.&rdquo;
Example:
&ldquo;Write a password policy for a 50-person fintech startup. Plain language. Include sections for: minimum requirements, MFA, password managers, and breach response. No corporate fluff.&rdquo;
The Meta Rule The more context you give, the more useful the output. Specify:
Your role (security engineer, CISO, junior analyst) Your audience (developers, executives, regulators) The format you want (table, bullet list, numbered steps, prose) Constraints (keep it under 200 words, no jargon, assume no prior knowledge) AI isn&rsquo;t a replacement for security expertise. It&rsquo;s a force multiplier for the expertise you already have — but only if you tell it exactly what you need.

Question 1: Source Code Vulnerabilities Analysis This question presents a vulnerable Java code snippet and asks you to identify all security flaws.
Identified Vulnerabilities Encoding Issue: Use of obsolete ISO-8859-1 charset and encoding. Instead use UTF-8 (Line 2) Hardcoded Credentials: Hard-coded username &ldquo;root&rdquo; present in connection string (Line 12) Weak Authentication: Database connection accepts empty passwords (Line 12) SQL Injection: The code directly concatenates user input (order_id) into the SQL query without sanitization (Line 14) Resource Leaks: Missing proper closure of database connections, statements, and result sets; absent try-catch blocks Outdated Driver: Uses deprecated com.mysql.jdbc.Driver instead of newer com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver (Line 11) Input Validation Missing: No validation on order_id parameter, risking XSS and HTML injection (Line 10) Exception Handling: Exceptions lack proper handling throughout the code How to Fix Each Vulnerability SQL Injection → Use Parameterised Queries
// Vulnerable String query = &#34;SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = &#34; + order_id; // Fixed PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(&#34;SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = ?&#34;); ps.setString(1, order_id); Hardcoded Credentials → Use Environment Variables or Secrets Manager
// Vulnerable String user = &#34;root&#34;; String pass = &#34;&#34;; // Fixed String user = System.getenv(&#34;DB_USER&#34;); String pass = System.getenv(&#34;DB_PASS&#34;); Resource Leaks → Use Try-with-Resources
try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass); PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(query); ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) { // use resources } // auto-closed Input Validation → Validate and Sanitise
if (!order_id.matches(&#34;^[0-9]+$&#34;)) { throw new IllegalArgumentException(&#34;Invalid order ID&#34;); } Why This Matters in Interviews Secure code review is a core skill for security engineers. When asked to review code, work through each layer systematically:
Input handling and validation Authentication and authorisation Data access patterns (SQL, NoSQL) Error handling and logging Secrets management Dependencies and versions Part of a series on real security engineer interview questions from major tech companies.
